XPONENTIAL FITNESS, INC. (NYSE: XPOF)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, reported May 7, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Revenue fell to $60.7m in Q1 FY26 from $76.9m in Q1 FY25, down (21%) / ($16.2m) YoY, driven by brand divestitures, fewer equipment installs, and a shift to outsourced merchandise (franchise (6%), equipment (61%), merchandise (90%)). Same-store sales fell (6%) in Q1 FY26. Revenue was $314.9m in FY25 vs $320.3m in FY24, down (2%).

> Profitability: As a franchisor, XPOF reports no traditional gross margin; the mix shift to high-margin royalties is margin-accretive. Operating margin expanded to 21.4% in Q1 FY26 from 12.6% in Q1 FY25, with operating income of $13.0m in Q1 FY26 vs $9.7m in Q1 FY25 on a (34%) SG&A cut. Net loss narrowed to ($0.8m) in Q1 FY26 from ($2.7m) in Q1 FY25, though $14.5m of interest expense in Q1 FY26 absorbed most operating gains. For the full year, net loss narrowed to ($53.7m) in FY25 from ($98.7m) in FY24, with Adjusted EBITDA of $111.8m vs $116.2m.

> Cash Flows: Operating cash flow swung to a ($21.7m) outflow in Q1 FY26 from $5.8m provided in Q1 FY25, hit by upfront legal-settlement payments and working capital. Cash fell to $21.5m at March 31, 2026 from $45.9m at year-end 2025.

> Liquidity and debt position: Cash and restricted cash were $21.5m at March 31, 2026, down (53%) from $45.9m at year-end 2025. Gross debt is ~$524.0m as of Q1 FY26, priced at a punitive ~10.5% margin over reference rates, with $14.5m of quarterly interest. Stockholders' deficit was ($372.0m) at quarter-end. The Up-C structure (85.1% LLC ownership) complicates the capital stack.

> Working Capital: The $39.75m combined FTC and franchisee settlements — $17.0m over 12 months and $22.75m over 35 months — are a defined near-term cash drain against just $21.5m of cash as of Q1 FY26.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: Portfolio cut from 10 to 5 core brands via divestitures; 140 studios closed in FY25. About 30% of contracted studio licenses were 12+ months behind schedule as of Q1 FY26, classified inactive.

> Regulatory & Litigation Overhang: The core risk: a $17.0m FTC settlement and $22.75m franchisee settlement, both finalized in 2026, an ongoing U.S. Attorney criminal probe, and securities class actions — all stemming from the 2023 Fuzzy Panda report.

> Management Change: Deep instability: founder-CEO Geisler ousted in May 2024 amid the federal probe; successor Mark King resigned in 2025; Mike Nuzzo named CEO in August 2025; an interim CFO remains in place as of Q1 FY26.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. FY25 results on February 26, 2026 and Q1 FY26 results on May 7, 2026 were filed on schedule, with no Form 12b-25 extension.

